  "text": "Django implements comprehensive SQL injection prevention across multiple layers:\n\n1. **RawSQL Expression Sanitization** (django/db/models/expressions.py:1236): The RawSQL class allows developers to write raw SQL expressions while enforcing parameterization. It accepts both SQL and params separately, ensuring that parameters are never concatenated into the SQL string.\n\n2. **Raw QuerySet Method Parameter Binding** (django/db/models/query.py:1461): The QuerySet.raw() method creates a RawQuerySet instance (line 2210) that accepts raw_query and params arguments. The RawQuerySet internally uses the RawQuery class (django/db/models/sql/query.py:150) which has a _execute_query() method (line 203) that properly parameterizes the SQL using the database connection's cursor.execute() method.\n\n3. **Cursor.execute() Parameterization Enforcement** (django/db/backends/utils.py): The CursorWrapper class (line 17) and CursorDebugWrapper class (line 117) wrap all database cursors and intercept execute() calls. The _execute() method (line 94) enforces that parameters are passed separately from the SQL string to the underlying database driver's cursor.execute() method, preventing string concatenation-based SQL injection.\n\n4. **Parameter Adaptation** (django/db/models/sql/query.py:203-220): Before execution, parameters are adapted using connection.ops.adapt_unknown_value() to handle type conversions appropriate for the database backend, ensuring all values are properly handled by the database driver.\n\n5. **Value Expression Parameterization** (django/db/models/expressions.py:1144): The Value class ensures that literal values in expressions are parameterized through its as_sql() method (line 1167), which returns parameters separately from SQL placeholders.\n\n6. **Extra SQL Parameter Binding** (django/db/models/query.py:1876): The QuerySet.extra() method allows raw SQL fragments but enforces parameter binding through the Query.add_extra() method (django/db/models/sql/query.py:2437) which pairs placeholder markers with their parameters.\n\n7. **Database-Specific Quoting** (django/db/backends/base/operations.py:413): The quote_name() method and its backend-specific implementations (MySQL: django/db/backends/mysql/operations.py:173, PostgreSQL: django/db/backends/postgresql/operations.py:189, Oracle: django/db/backends/oracle/operations.py:391, SQLite: django/db/backends/sqlite3/operations.py:167) properly escape identifier names using database-specific quoting mechanisms.\n\n8. **Lookup Parameter Binding** (django/db/models/lookups.py): All Lookup classes implement as_sql() methods that return SQL with parameters separated, ensuring WHERE clause conditions are parameterized.\n\n9. **WHERE Clause Parameter Management** (django/db/models/sql/where.py): The WhereNode (line 21) and ExtraWhere (line 334) classes manage WHERE clause fragments with associated parameters, maintaining separation between SQL and parameters throughout compilation.\n\n10. **Compiler-Level SQL Generation** (django/db/models/sql/compiler.py): The SQLCompiler and specialized compilers generate SQL with parameterized queries, calling cursor.execute() with separate params argument (lines 1631, 1939, 2160).\n\nThe comprehensive chain of SQL injection prevention flows from user-facing APIs (raw(), extra(), Value expressions) through parameter adaptation, identifier quoting, expression compilation, and finally to parameterized cursor execution at the database driver level."
